    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. you mentioned it's harder to predict than regular turbulence though. is there anything specifically about the way the air moves in CAT that makes it so much more sudden or \"unpredictable\" compared to, say, turbulence near a storm front?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "One key aspect that makes CAT more unpredictable is the way the wind shear interacts with the plane's wings. In traditional turbulence near a storm front, the wind shear is often more gradual and predictable, as the storm front is a large-scale weather system with a defined boundary. In contrast, CAT is often caused by a more localized and subtle interaction between the jet stream and the plane's flight path.\n\nImagine a plane flying through a narrow, winding river of air, where the wind speed and direction change rapidly over a short distance. This is similar to what happens in CAT, where the wind shear can change suddenly and unpredictably, creating a steep slope or a sudden drop in altitude. The plane may not have enough time to react to this change, resulting in a more sudden and unexpected turbulence event.\n\nAdditionally, CAT can be caused by a phenomenon called \"wind shear layers,\" which are thin layers of air with varying wind speeds and directions. These layers can be difficult to detect, as they may not be visible on radar or other weather forecasts. The plane may fly through one of these layers without warning, resulting in a sudden and unexpected turbulence event.",
      "source": "target",
